## Environment and Dataset Paths

- Refer to `CLAUDE.md` for the current environment snapshot and dataset addresses.
- Keep `AGENTS.md` focused on stable rules rather than volatile environment details.

## Canonical State

- `PROJECT_STATE.json`: stage and milestone state. Stage transitions require explicit user confirmation.
- `iteration_log.json`: experiment history and best iteration. `$iterate` owns writes here.
- `project_map.json`: stable implementation map for core code and configs.
- `MEMORY.md`: human-readable append-only lessons and decisions. `iteration_log.json` remains the machine source of truth.
- `OPERATOR_CONTEXT.md`: optional operator preferences. It may guide defaults, but it is not evidence for project facts. Write it only from explicit operator input; later stages read it without inferring new preferences.
- `.evidence/`: evidence-chain artifacts for compiled current docs when the dynamic context layout is enabled.
- `.auto_iterate/`: controller-owned runtime state (if auto-iterate is enabled; do not edit manually).
- These canonical state files must stay at the repository root, not under `.agents/`.

## Context Layers

- Read `.agents/references/context-layering-policy.md` and `.agents/references/research-invariants.md` before research planning, documentation, iteration, auto-iteration, or release work.
- Current fact-layer summaries belong in `docs/20_facts/`; they must come from project artifacts or evidence chains.
- Research evidence belongs in `docs/30_evidence/`; it records sources and candidate norms, not permanent rules.
- Dynamic protocol drafts belong in `docs/35_protocol/`; they are project-local and evidence-derived.
- Human-approved contracts belong in `docs/10_contract/`; they override protocol drafts and operator preferences.
- Current project facts must come from current repo artifacts, logs, configs, metrics, or evidence chains, not from memory alone.

## Language Policy

- Match the language of the latest substantive user input unless the user explicitly requests another language.
- Use the same language for natural-language artifacts, reports, and summaries unless the user asks for a different output language.
- Keep file names, paths, commands, code identifiers, JSON/YAML keys, schema fields, workflow IDs, metric keys, and placeholder tokens in English.
- Treat English wording in templates and examples under `.agents/` as structural guidance only, not as a requirement that the final output be in English.

## Skills

- Use `$orchestrator` for stage status, gating, rollback, and project-level decisions.
- Use `$init-project` for WF0 compact guidance setup, staged guidance refresh, and explicit operator-context updates.
- Use `$doc-compiler` for contract, fact, protocol, or release docs that need evidence-chain JSON.
- Use `$protocol-compiler` to compile `docs/30_evidence/**` into reviewable `docs/35_protocol/**` drafts without field profiles.
- Use `$protocol-drift-check` before turning protocol drafts into contracts or before WF5/WF10/WF11/WF12 gates in dynamic-context projects.
- Use `$review-packet` when the operator needs a short approval/revision/rejection packet for a dynamic-context gate.
- After explicit human approval for a contract, use `tooling/evidence/approve_contract.py` and then re-run the dynamic-context gate.
- Use `$iterate` for WF10 `plan -> code -> run -> eval`.
- Use `$code-expert` only for first-pass implementation from the roadmap and project map.
- Use `$code-debug` for post-WF8 implementation code changes, bug fixes, or iteration-driven edits under `src/`, `scripts/`, `configs/`, or `project_map.json`.
- Use `$harness-maintenance` for Codex hooks, skill contracts, skill routing/triggers, permission policy, `.agents/.claude` skill alignment, and Harness guardrail tests or docs.
- Use `$code-review` for review-only checks of code, diffs, and code-backed docs:
  light during codebase understanding, medium after code changes, heavy when
  docs, evidence chains, release claims, or gate packets depend on the code.
- Use `$evaluate` for experiment analysis and per-iteration reports.
- Use `$idea-debate` as WF2 after WF1 to skeptically compare directions before refinement.
- Use `$refine-idea` as WF3 to turn survey and debate into a feasible, testable idea without architecture design.
- Use `$refine-arch` as WF6 after WF4/WF5 evidence to design the MVP architecture.
- Use `$build-plan` as WF7 to translate architecture into files, tests, and `project_map.json`.
- Use the stage-specific skills only for their intended outputs.

## Entry Scripts

- Refer to `CLAUDE.md` for the locked core entry scripts.
- Auxiliary scripts may exist under `scripts/`, but they must not fork or duplicate the core train/eval path.

## Stable Code Rules

- Before editing `src/`, `scripts/`, `tests/`, durable configs, or supporting utilities, read `.agents/references/code-style.md` and apply its pre-edit checklist.
- Read `.agents/references/project-map-rule.md` and `project_map.json` before any non-trivial stable-code change.
- Use `.agents/references/ubiquitous-language.md` for workflow terms and maintain `docs/20_facts/Project_Glossary.md` for project-specific codebase vocabulary.
- Distinguish Conclusion Evidence from Gate Evidence; do not use bare `evidence` when the meaning is ambiguous.
- Update `project_map.json` when stable files are added, removed, renamed, or when interfaces, exports, or tensor shapes change.
- Keep code changes small, readable, and fail-fast; avoid unrelated refactors and broad fallback behavior.
- Use `.agents/references/project-map-rule.md` to decide stable vs volatile scope.

## Code Review Rules

- For `$code-review`, follow `.agents/skills/code-review/SKILL.md` and
  `.agents/skills/code-review/references/review-report.md`.
- Code review is review-only. Do not edit subject code, current docs, canonical
  state, or `.evidence/**`; route ordinary code fixes through `$code-debug` and
  guardrail fixes through `$harness-maintenance`.
- Medium and heavy reviews must record git metadata, changed line ranges,
  reviewer statuses, reconciled findings, and a Gate ledger.
- Heavy reviews for docs, evidence chains, release claims, or stage gates must
  attempt independent Codex and DeepSeek review, or record `NOT_RUN` with the
  reason and compensating checks.

## Training Rules

- Before running training after training-related code changes, create a semantic commit:
  - `train(research): {what changed and why}`
  - `train(baseline/<name>): {what changed and why}`
- After Python edits, run `python -m py_compile` and `ruff check --select=E,F,I` on modified files.
- Preserve core train/eval logic in the locked entry scripts referenced from `CLAUDE.md`.
- Use `.agents/references/pre-training-rule.md` for run-traceability requirements.

## Workflow Control

- Never auto-advance a workflow stage without explicit user confirmation.
- Use `.agents/references/workflow-guide.md` for the full stage flow and detailed skill behavior.
- For every stage transition, current-doc write, stable-code change, canonical-state edit, or WF10/WF11/WF12 readiness check, follow the gate ledger format in `.agents/references/workflow-guide.md` and report command, result, reason, and updated artifacts.
- High-risk skills may have machine-readable contracts in `.agents/skill-contracts/contracts.json`; satisfy the required read set before write actions and follow required/forbidden actions.
- Use `.agents/references/contract-gating-rule.md` before implementation, validation, iteration, auto-iteration, and release.
- Use `$protocol-drift-check` when evidence, open questions, negative results, or iteration decisions may have invalidated `docs/35_protocol/**`.
- When writing docs, follow `.agents/references/documentation-evidence-rule.md`: re-read source artifacts and list evidence rather than relying on memory.
- For compiled current docs, also follow `.agents/references/evidence-chain-rule.md`: write evidence_chain, source_manifest, and doc_audit before replacing current Markdown.
- Also follow `.agents/references/documentation-style.md`: keep docs concise, human-readable, use ASCII flow diagrams for workflows, and archive replaced docs under `docs/90_legacy/`.
- Use `.agents/references/lesson-quality-rule.md` before promoting lessons into `MEMORY.md`.
